  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are numerous international laws and conventions aimed at combating money laundering. Here's a breakdown of some of the most important ones:\n\n**Key International Conventions and Organizations:**\n\n*   **Financial Action Task Force (FATF):**\n    *   Not a treaty or law itself, but the **global standard-setting body** for anti-money laundering (AML) and counter-terrorist financing (CTF).\n    *   Develops and promotes policies and recommendations to combat money laundering and terrorist financing.\n    *   Issues the **40 Recommendations** on Money Laundering and the **9 Special Recommendations** on Terrorist Financing.  These are the internationally recognized standards.\n    *   Monitors countries' implementation of these standards through mutual evaluations and publishes reports.\n    *   Maintains a list of countries with strategic AML/CTF deficiencies.\n\n*   **United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988 Vienna Convention):**\n    *   One of the earliest international treaties to address money laundering.\n    *   Requires countries to criminalize the laundering of proceeds derived from drug trafficking.\n    *   Promotes international cooperation in investigations and prosecutions.\n\n*   **United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000 Palermo Convention):**\n    *   Expands the scope of money laundering offenses beyond drug trafficking to include proceeds from a wide range of transnational crimes (e.g., human trafficking, corruption, arms trafficking).\n    *   Requires countries to criminalize the laundering of proceeds from these crimes.\n    *   Promotes international cooperation in investigations, prosecutions, and asset recovery.\n\n*   **United Nations Convention against Corruption (2003 Merida Convention):**\n    *   Addresses money laundering related to corruption offenses.\n    *   Requires countries to criminalize the laundering of proceeds of corruption.\n    *   Promotes asset recovery of funds stolen through corruption.\n\n*   **Council of Europe Convention on Laundering, Search, Seizure and Confiscation of the Proceeds from Crime (1990 Strasbourg Convention):**\n    *   A regional treaty applicable to Council of Europe member states.\n    *   Establishes common standards for criminalizing money laundering, asset forfeiture, and international cooperation.\n\n*   **Council of Europe Convention on Laundering, Search, Seizure and Confiscation of the Proceeds from Crime and on the Financing of Terrorism (2005 Warsaw Convention):**\n    *   Updates the Strasbourg Convention to include provisions on combating terrorist financing.\n\n*   **International Monetary Fund (IMF) and World Bank:**\n    *   Play a role in combating money laundering through technical assistance to countries to improve their AML/CTF frameworks.\n    *   Assess countries' compliance with the FATF standards as part of their financial sector assessments.\n\n**Key Principles and Obligations:**\n\nThese international laws and conventions generally require countries to:\n\n*   **Criminalize money laundering:**  Establish criminal offenses for laundering the proceeds of crime.\n*   **Implement customer due diligence (CDD) measures:**  Financial institutions must identify and verify the identities of their customers and understand the nature of their business.\n*   **Maintain records:** Financial institutions must keep records of transactions and customer information.\n*   **Report suspicious transactions:**  Financial institutions must report suspicious transactions to a financial intelligence unit (FIU).\n*   **Cooperate internationally:**  Provide mutual legal assistance to other countries in investigations and prosecutions.\n*   **Confiscate assets:**  Seize and confiscate assets derived from or used in money laundering.\n*   **Establish a financial intelligence unit (FIU):**  A central agency to receive, analyze, and disseminate suspicious transaction reports.\n\n**In summary:**  A robust network of international laws, conventions, and standards exists to combat money laundering. The FATF plays a crucial role in setting the standards and monitoring countries' compliance. These international efforts aim to prevent criminals from using the financial system to hide and legitimize the proceeds of their illegal activities. The exact implementation of these international standards varies by country, but the overall framework is widely adopted.\n",
